ets. The studies reveal surprising differences in housing investment in the two countries. For example, because down payments in Japan are much higher than in the United States, Japanese tend to delay home purchases relative to their American counterparts. In the United States, the advent of home equity credit may have reduced private saving overall. This book is the first comparison of housing markets in Japan and the United States, and its findings illuminate the effects of housing markets on productivity growth, business investment, and trade.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBusiness. 0aHousing -- Japan -- Congresses. 0aHousing -- United States -- Congresses. 0aHousing. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  amarketplace, house, home, living, real estate, usa, america, american, japanese, eastern, western, international, global, economy, economics, wealth, finance, financial, standards, comparison, contrast, income, savings, social studies, sociological, sociology, essay collection, prices, homeowner, commute, public, policy, policies, rent, down payment, equity, credit.1 aCase, Karl E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHatta, Tatsuo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHendershott, Patric H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIto, Takatoshi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoguchi, Yukio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoguchi, Yukio, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOhkawara, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPoterba, James M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPoterba, James M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel